" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 65 "H := x^5-x^2-2*x;  fact
or(H);  factor(H,real); factor(H,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#>%\"HG,(*$)%\"xG\"\"&\"\"\"F**$)F(\"\"#F*!\"\"*&F-F*F(F
*F." }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(%\"xG\"\"\",&F$F%F%F%F%,**$)F
$\"\"$F%F%*$)F$\"\"#F%!\"\"F$F%F-F.F%" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 
"6#**,&%\"xG\"\"\"$F&\"\"!F&F&F%F&,&F%F&$\"+k*4KN\"!\"*!\"\"F&,(*$)F%
\"\"#F&F&*&$\"+U'*4KN!#5F&F%F&F&$\"+Vs'zZ\"F,F&F&" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*,,&%\"xG\"\"\"$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&^$$\"+@)\\gw\"!#5$\"+>
3#G?\"!\"*F&F&,&F%F&^$F+$!+>3#G?\"F0F&F&F%F&,&F%F&$\"+k*4KN\"F0!\"\"F&
" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In \+
those cases where Maple did not find enough linear factors, there is a
 reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an assumption that if the coef
ficients of a polynomial are all given exactly (as integers or rationa
l numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are only interested in findin
g exact factors (factors where the coefficients are integers or ration
al numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra doesn't guarantee tha
t the factors of  a polynomial will necessarily have the same kind of \+
coefficients as the polynomial, only the polynomial can be factored.  \+
You can force Maple to report additional (approximate) factors.  For e
xample,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6
#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 
"> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
{XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#!\"\"F&,&F%F&F'F&F&,&F%F&
F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term is called a " }{TEXT 280 
18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding it tells Maple to consid
er additonal factors where the coefficients are allowed to include ele
ments from the field extension.  It is fairly clear from the factorizt
ion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all by itself that something
 involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included.  However, there are pr
oblems where there is not a obvious clue as to which specific field ex
tension should be added.  If you are willing to accept an appropriate \+
solution, then using the field extension " }{TEXT 282 4 "real" }{TEXT 
-1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomial using a floating point a
pproximation scheme.  For example, consider (here I am pretending I do
n't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optimal):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" 
}}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F
&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,r
eal);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F
&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" 
{TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "Finally, the Fundamental \+
Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a polynomial of degree " }
{TEXT 283 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 
53 " real linear factors.  Rather, only hat it will have " }{TEXT 285 
1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What is the difference?  Some o
f the factors may involve complex roots rather than real roots.  For e
xample compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> \+
" 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
*&,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" 
