" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 380 "A related theorem about finding root
s of polynomials (equivalently factoring polynomials into a product of
 linear factors) asserts that if the polynomial has real coefficients \+
-- all of the polynomials we have considered (and will consider) have \+
had real coefficients -- then any complex roots (or factors) must occu
r in conjugate pairs.  For example, both the complex factors of " }
{TEXT 288 5 "F, G " }{TEXT -1 4 "and " }{TEXT 289 2 "H " }{TEXT -1 
236 "(above) all occurred in conjugate pairs.  Demonstrate this theore
m by creating three new polynomials, name them F1, G1 and H1, of degre
e 5, 6 and 7, resp., and show that the any complex factors of F1, G1 a
nd H1 occur in conjugate pairs." }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 60 "F1:=x^5-10; factor(F1); fact
or(F1,real); factor(F1,complex);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#>%
